                            There is substance in what Nitish Kumar says. While it is a common practice to talk of India as a country, it has to be borne in mind that India is not a homogenous entity. In reality, it is a conglomeration of many states and erstwhile kingdoms. The country of India emerged after centuries of Mughal and British rule. Prior to them the sub continent was ruled by hundreds of kings and rulers who ruled over small parts of the land. The vestiges of this historical past are still in evidence everywhere. The only time that the common man thinks of India as a country is when there is an international cricket match between India and other countries, or during times of crisis like a war. Otherwise, most people of the country think more in terms of their state, their religion and their caste. So, for all of Modi's talk about building the nation, it is just not possible by treating the country as a monolithic whole where one rule only applies. The RSS vision of the country is not based in reality, but a figment of imagination borne during British rule. Their 'Bharat Mata' is non-existent in real life. The sooner Narendra Modi, the BJP and the RSS realize this, the better. Unless states are brought into confidence, and developmental measures are taken after consensus with the states, the BJP is bound to lose in the long term. Their north Indian based Brahminical vision for the country is not acceptable to many in the country. It is not just Modi who is running the BJP. The RSS and other right wing groups are also hard at work behind the scenes. There are several fringe elements comprising of north Indian Hindi chauvinists, Brahmins, other so called upper caste apologists and sundry narrow minded groups with hidden agendas who are at work behind the scenes. Sooner or later, these elements are bound to come out with their handiwork, and it will lay the seeds for the BJP's downfall.
