Author::::<a href="http://social.ndtv.com/groups.php?id=696266" target="_blank">Observer</a>

Comment::::<div class="com_user_text">
                            Lets forget for a moment that Nitish has done a lot of political blunders and think about the issue. <br/>
The tax collected by the center is ultimately spent on the people whether it is through states or through central plans or any other method. In the new scheme, the weight of population has decreased, while for area and forest cover it has increased. Meaning Bihar would get lesser share in the direct devolution because of its small area and small forest cover (only 6.5%). Also, it would lose on the account of planned schemes and backward region grant fund (36 out 38 districts of Bihar received funds under this).. <br/>
The new devolution formula is rational. But a state like Bihar that is already grappling with resource crunch has to be provided a short term package to compensate the immediate loss, just like Tamil Nadu would get in case of GST even though Tamil Nadu is not a poor state.. <br/>
But Tamil Nadu would actually get it, Bihar wont. Because people here have become pro party or pro personality (pro Modi or anti modi) and no one seems to be pro Bihar. Unfortunate it is!
